\paragraph{Manifold Approximation Analysis.}
As shown in Table~\ref{tab:site_comparison_metrics}, the FLOSS simulations yield a significantly lower manifold fit RMSE for the skin layer temperature. Because the aerodynamic smoothness of the snowpack dampens mechanical shear, the fast TKE coordinate is constrained tightly to the stable, non-turbulent residual sheet $\mathcal{M}_0^{\text{lam}}$ for the majority of the night, yielding a highly predictable, radiation-dominated thermodynamic surface state.

In contrast, the larger roughness length of CASES99 drives continuous, intermittent turbulence. The state-space trajectories of CASES99 undergo broader dynamic excursions across the linear boundary-mediated transition zone of the active critical manifold sheet $\mathcal{M}_0^{\text{act}}$. This active mixing naturally increases the geometric projection error (producing a higher regression RMSE) while maintaining a higher overall trajectory capture rate within the active turbulent envelope.